vectorData.altText: 12. Dorsal rami are typically larger than ventral rami.
That's right!  Dorsal rami innervate only the para-axial region of the body, and so are smaller than ventral rami, which innervate the remainder of the body, including the limbs.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

In the accompanying diagram, identify the spinal nerve. 
Notice that the spinal nerve, formed by the union of the ventral root (motor) and dorsal root (sensory) is a mixed nerve containing both motor and sensory fibres.
Identify the dorsal and ventral rami     . The dorsal and ventral rami are formed by the bifurcation      of the spinal nerve, and are therefore also mixed nerves.
Notice that the dorsal ramus is depicted as being smaller than the ventral ramus; this is because the dorsal ramus innervates a smaller portion of the body than the ventral ramus, as will be explained next.
Red arrows indicate the direction of information flow.
